osts. Fixed costs are treated as period costs and are not included in the unit cost. This approach helps in understanding the impact of variable costs on the overall profitability of a product or service. By excluding fixed costs from the unit cost calculation, marginal costing provides a clearer picture of the contribution margin and aids in short-term decision-making [Data: Concepts (177); Relationships (183, 184)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Traditional management accounting includes various techniques for cost control.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Traditional management accounting is inward-looking, focusing on controlling costs. The most important techniques include costing systems (marginal and absorption costing), budgeting systems, standard costing and variance analysis, and working capital management. These techniques help organizations monitor and control their expenses, ensuring that they operate within their budgetary constraints and achieve their financial targets. Traditional management accounting provides a foundation for more advanced and modern accounting methods [Data: Concepts (182); Relationships (174, 182)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Period costs are treated as expenses in the period they are incurred.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Period costs are fixed costs that are treated as expenses in the period in which they are incurred, rather than being included in the unit cost, as in marginal costing. This treatment of fixed costs helps in accurately reflecting the financial performance of an organization for a specific period. By recognizing period costs as expenses when they occur, organizations can better manage their cash flow and financial planning [Data: Concepts (190); Relationships (184)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Activity-based costing (ABC) provides a more meaningful product cost.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Activity-based costing (ABC) is a 